# HTML Documentation

## Requirement

All HTML files SHALL include appropriate comments and documentation for complex sections.

## File-Level Comments

HTML files SHOULD include a file-level comment at the beginning describing the file's purpose:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <!--
    User Profile Page
    Displays user information and profile settings.
    Template: Jinja2
  -->
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>User Profile</title>
</head>
```

## Section Comments

Complex sections of HTML SHOULD be documented with comments:

```html
<!-- Navigation Menu -->
<nav>
  <!-- Main navigation items -->
  <ul>...</ul>
  
  <!-- User account menu -->
  <div class="user-menu">...</div>
</nav>

<!-- Main Content Area -->
<main>
  <!-- User profile header -->
  <header>...</header>
  
  <!-- Profile settings form -->
  <form>...</form>
</main>
```

## Template Documentation

HTML files using template engines SHOULD document template variables and logic:

```html
<!--
  Template Variables:
  - user: User object with name, email, avatar
  - settings: UserSettings object
  - csrf_token: CSRF token for form submission
-->
<form method="post">
  <input type="hidden" name="csrf_token" value="{{ csrf_token }}">
  <input type="text" name="name" value="{{ user.name }}">
</form>
```

## Complex DOM Structures

Complex DOM structures SHOULD be documented:

```html
<!--
  Responsive Grid Layout:
  - Desktop: 3 columns
  - Tablet: 2 columns
  - Mobile: 1 column
  Uses CSS Grid with auto-fit
-->
<div class="grid-container">
  <div class="grid-item">...</div>
</div>
```

## Comment Style

HTML comments SHALL use the standard HTML comment syntax:

```html
<!-- Comment text here -->
```

Multi-line comments SHALL be formatted consistently:

```html
<!--
  Multi-line comment
  with additional details
-->
```

## What to Document

Comments SHOULD be used for:

- File purpose and context
- Complex DOM structures
- Template variables and logic
- Non-obvious implementation details
- Workarounds or temporary solutions
- Integration points with external systems

Comments SHALL NOT be used for:

- Obvious code (self-documenting HTML)
- Styling information (use CSS comments)
- Redundant information

## Comment Maintenance

Comments SHALL be kept up to date:

- When code changes, update related comments
- Remove outdated or incorrect comments
- Comments SHALL reflect the current implementation

## Accessibility Notes

When HTML includes accessibility features that may not be obvious, document them:

```html
<!--
  Skip link for keyboard navigation:
  Allows users to skip to main content
-->
<a href="#main-content" class="skip-link">Skip to main content</a>
```
